<p>Pac-Man for the 2600 was a bad port. The arcade original had been ported to hardware that couldn't handle its colour palette or smooth animation. Players who expected the arcade experience were disappointed. Atari shipped twelve million cartridges into a market of ten million consoles, assuming every owner would buy it on brand recognition alone. About seven million copies sold. The five million surplus units became the most visible emblem of the industry's hubris.</p>
